ligious from medical concerns, at which times and in what ways? Where have medicine and religion converged, and how has such knowledge been defined by scholars and cultural actors? Are ‘religion’ and ‘medicine’ the best terms by which scholars can grapple with knowledge about the sacred and the self, destiny and disease?  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 0aMedicinexReligious aspects. 0aMedicinezAsiaxReligious aspects. 0aMedicinezAsia. 4amanchesterhive variable pricing textbooks. 7aMEDICAL / History.2bisacsh  aAsian medicine.  aAsian religions.  aAyurveda.  aScience and Religion.  amedical anthropology.  areligion and medicine.  asituating knowledge.  asocial construction of medicine.  atraditional medicine.1 aBihari Mukharji, Projit, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCanavas, Constantin, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCerulli, Anthony, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCoderey, Céline, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLambert, Helen, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSamuel, Geoffrey, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSchäfer, Dagmar, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSivin, Nathan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aStanley-Baker, Michael, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aStanley-Baker, Michael, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aTriplett, Katja, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aValussi, Elena, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertManchester Universit